\begin_layout Abstract
We implemented and applied a hybrid approach for modelling the solvation
 of molecules where we combined a three-dimensional reference interaction
 site model (3D RISM) with quantum mechanical (QM) calculations of the solute.
 The electrostatic potential induced by the solute is derived directly from
 its electron density.
 For neutral solutes, we analyzed the accuracy of calculated solvation free
 energies which are mainly determined by the cavity formation energy.
 As a second contribution, the solute electronic structure relaxation in
 an aqueous medium also has a noticeable influence on the results of SCF-RISM
 calculations.
 By applying a known partial molar volume correction, for which we give
 an alternative interpretation, our hybrid model shows results in good agreement
 with experiment and results calculated with a polarizable continuum model
 (PCM).
 As a model with an atomic solvent representation, RISM accounts for the
 effect of discrete hydrogen bonds which is included only on average in
 PCM models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
Solvation free energy, self-consistent reference interaction site model,
 partial molar volume correction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solvent environment of a molecule can considerably affect its properties
 and thus also change the products as well as the rate of its chemical reactions
 and even the mechanism of such transformations.
 Therefore, modelling solvation effects is of central importance for understandi
ng many chemical reactions of organic and inorganic species as well as for
 industrial applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 Examples of pertinent application fields, also of industrial importance,
 are catalytic reactions for the production of hydrogen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lewis06"

\end_inset

, the conversion of CO
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Roy10"

\end_inset

, transformations of biomass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ragauskas06"

\end_inset

, and the complex chemistry of actinides in aqueous solution, which is highly
 relevant for the nuclear fuel cycle and radioactive waste disposal 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Choppin06"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In support of current experimental efforts in various areas of chemistry
 and materials science in aqueous media, computational studies are needed
 to examine or predict species and processes at the atomic level.
 One of the two most popular strategies in computational chemistry for studying
 solution systems is the combination of quantum mechanics (QM) calculations
 with implicit solvation models, e.g., the polarizable continuum model (PCM)
 and its variants, based the conductor-like solvation model (COSMO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Klamt95,Tomasi05"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, despite the importance of solvation models, these implicit methods
 do not provide insight into the structure and the statistical fluctuations
 of the solvent.
 Another approach to solvation is the so-called explicit solvation model,
 where one treats solute and solvent equivalently by performing molecular
 dynamics (MD) simulation from first principle (ab initio MD – AIMD) or
 MD simulations based on a force-field (molecular mechanics – MM) description
 of both the solute and the solvent medium (MM-MD).
 However, the statistical sampling of large numbers of solvent configurations
 entails significant computational cost.
 Therefore QM dynamic simulations are restricted to models with a comparably
 small numbers of solvent molecules.
 The MM solvent description of MM-MD or hybrid QM/MM methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gao96,Gao92"

\end_inset

 reduce the computational cost.
 Yet, the results of statistical sampling are only as good as the effective
 force field used to parameterize the solvent-solvent and solute-solvent
 interactions.
 Also, to compete with continuum models in reproducing electrostatic interaction
s, one has to account for the polarizability of the solvent medium 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leontyev11"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the difficulties mentioned above, strategies which combine QM methods
 with integral equation theory of molecular liquids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03,book:Hansen06"

\end_inset

 are regarded as a promising direction to study ions and complexes and their
 chemical reactions in aqueous solution with sufficient accuracy and at
 affordable cost.
 One successful approach of this type is the reference interaction site
 model (RISM) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chandler72"

\end_inset

 which provides solvation (free) energies and also averaged solvent structures
 via site-site radial distribution functions (RDF).
 The hybrid approach of RISM together with a self-consistent field (SCF)
 QM solute description was first proposed at the level of Hartree-Fock theory
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tenno93"

\end_inset

.
 Later-on Kohn-Sham density functional theory (KS-DFT) was combined with
 3D RISM to investigate the electronic structure of a metal–water interface
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

.
 Thus far, several implementations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato00,Du03,Gusarov06,Casanova07,Kloss08,Yoshida11,Yoshida14"

\end_inset

 combine RISM theory with a state-of-the-art QM method to provide an alternative
 approach for classical implicit and explicit solvation models.
 The applications of the hybrid RISM-SCF method has successfully ben applied
 to calculate acidity and basicity, the chemical equilibrium and the molecular
 structure as well as chemical reactions and excited states in solution
 systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03,Sato13"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mainly two factors determine the solvent effect in the SCF-RISM method,
 the contributions of the solute electronic relaxation and the excess chemical
 potential 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 The excess chemical potential, which measures the free energy change of
 coupling a solute molecule to the solvent, serves as the approximation
 of the solvation free energy in MM-RISM methods.
 The excess chemical potential calculated from 3D RISM is well known 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

 to overestimate the energy required for the formation of the solute cavity.
 Thus 3D RISM poorly predicts the thermodynamics of hydrophobic hydration
 of neutral solutes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kovalenko00a"

\end_inset

.
 To overcome this weakness, several correction methods of the solvation
 free energy have been proposed, including the repulsive bridge correction
 (RBC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03,Kovalenko00a"

\end_inset

, the cavity formation energy correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Truchon14"

\end_inset

 and the 
\color blue
partial
\color inherit
 molar volume (PMV) correction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Palmer10,Sergiievskyi14,Misin15"

\end_inset

.
 These correction methods are mainly applied in MM-RISM calculations, in
 which the solute electronic structure is assumed not to be relaxed.
 Yet, as in the PCM method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Orozco07"

\end_inset

, the energy due to the electronic relaxation of the solute is not negligible
 in the SCF-RISM method.
 The change of the solvation free energy due to solute polarization is almost
 proportional to this term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato13,Sato07a"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
BL: linear response regime is mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato07a"

\end_inset

, they claimed 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Delta\mu\sim-2E_{reorg}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 but the influence of solute polarization on the accuracy of the solvation
 free energy has not been well studied in SCF-RISM calculations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, we examine in the following the accuracy of the solvation free
 energy in hybrid QM RISM calculations for a test set of 43 neutral organic
 solute molecules in aqueous solution.
 The test solutes include hydrocarbon chains and aromatic rings, and various
 organic molecules with functional groups.
 A list of all species is given in the Supporting Information (SI).
 We explore the effect of solute electronic relaxation in stepwise fashion.
 Starting from MM-RISM as a reference, we introduce the polarization of
 the solute in the solvent medium, first by applying first-order perturbation
 theory (PT1-RISM), going on to a second-order perturbation theory treatment
 (PT2-RISM), and finally moving on to the full SCF-RISM relaxation.
 For all method variants, we compare the performance of the recently reported
 PMV correction term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sergiievskyi14"

\end_inset

 to the solvation free energy.
 To analyze the accuracy the RISM approach, we discuss these results in
 comparison to those of PCM calculations and to experiment.
\end_layout

