\begin_layout Subsection
Interaction between QM solute and RISM solvent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the 3D RISM MM theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

, the solute interaction potential acting on solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is derived from the site-specific contribution of a solvent-solute interaction
 defined as the sum of the Lennard-Jones (LJ) and Coulomb terms.
 The LJ energy term, 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\text{LJ}}=4\sum_{i\alpha}\epsilon_{i\alpha}\left[(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r_{i\alpha})^{12}-(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r_{i\alpha})^{6}\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i\alpha}=|\vec{r}_{i}-\vec{r}_{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

, accounts for short-range repulsion and dispersion interactions and is
 the sum of pairwise site-site contributions between solute and solvent
 site 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, respectively, as in the MM case.
 The electrostatic interaction between the charge density of the QM solute
 and the charged solvent sites reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U^{\text{C}}=\int n_{\text{v}}(\vec{r})f_{\text{C}}(|\vec{r}-\vec{r}'|)n_{\text{u}}(\vec{r}')d^{3}rd^{3}r'.\label{eq:solute-solvent-interaction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 are the solvent and the solute charge densities, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{C}}(r)=1/r$
\end_inset

 is the Coulomb kernel.
 In self-consistent calculations this expression for the electrostatic interacti
ons is used to define two types of potentials, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{u}}=f_{\text{C}}\ast n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{v}}=f_{\text{C}}\ast n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

, acting on charged solvent sites and the solute charges (electrons and
 nucleus), respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strategy for evaluating these two potentials differs slightly due to
 the nature of the charged densities 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

.
 The solvent charge density, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}=\rho\sum_{\alpha}q_{\alpha}g_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, appearing in the expression for the solvent electrostatic potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

, represents statistical average that is represented on a uniform Cartesian
 grid.
 For a neutral solute, the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 The corresponding potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{v }}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by solving the Poisson equation with periodic boundary
 conditions, using fast Fourier transform techniques.
 For neutral solutes with typical dipole moments and a sufficiently large
 unit cell this may be justified 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Makov95"

\end_inset

.
