\begin_layout Standard
The solute charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

, on the other hand, is the sum of the distributed electron density and
 localized atomic core densities, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}=n_{\text{e}}+n_{\text{n}}$
\end_inset

, the latter representing atomic nuclei or effective core charges: 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{n}}(\vec{r})=\sum_{i}z_{i}\delta(\vec{r}-\vec{r}_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we apply a simplified Ewald scheme where the convolution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{n}}^{\prime}=p\ast n_{\text{n}}$
\end_inset

 of the singular charge density with a unit Gaussian kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

