\begin_layout Subsection
Free energy functionals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In electronic DFT, the ground state of the electronic structure of a solute
 in the gas phase is determined by minimizing the Kohn–Sham energy functional
 with respect to the electronic density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochDFT"

\end_inset

.
 For brevity we express the energy as a functional of the solute charge
 density, 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding ground-state charge density of the solute.
 The distribution of the site charges of the solute force-field yields a
 coarse approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 Correspondingly, RISM calculations of the excess chemical potential with
 a discrete force-field and a delocalized gas-phase charge distribution
 as input will give two approximations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, for the excess chemical potential of the solute in the solvent environment.
 The corresponding two values for the free energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{MM}}=E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]+\mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{PT1}}=E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]+\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 will be referred to as MM and PT1 in this work.
 The first-order perturbation theory (PT1) expression 
\color blue
is derived from a
\color inherit
 self-consistent field (SCF) QM+RISM model with a free-energy 
\color blue
functional,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G[n_{\text{u}}]=E[n_{\text{u}}]+\mu[n_{\text{u}}],\label{eq:free-energy-functional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color blue
by evaluating
\color inherit
 the free energy functional 
\begin_inset Formula $G[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

 at the unperturbed gas-phase charge distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 The hybrid QM+RISM free energy functional, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:free-energy-functional"

\end_inset

, will be, in general, minimized by the self-consistent solution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

.
 The self-consistent model and the corresponding free energy will be labeled
 by “SCF”, i.e.
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{SCF}}=G[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

.
 In the following, it will be more convenient to operate with the free energy
 values offset by 
\begin_inset Formula $-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, the energy of the solute in the gas phase.
 Then these deviations 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 read 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta G_{\text{MM}} & = & \mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\nonumber \\
\Delta G_{\text{PT1}} & = & \mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\nonumber \\
\Delta G_{\text{SCF}} & = & \left(E[n_{\text{u}}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\right)+\mu[n_{\text{u}}]\label{eq:dG-models-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{\text{SCF}}=E[n_{\text{u}}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 in the last equation is the energy due to the solute polarization by the
 solvent, a non-negative quantity for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

