\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity assume a model is characterized by a single degree of freedom
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such as a dipole moment.
 Minimization of an energy expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e[d]=a(d-d_{0})^{2}/2,
\]

\end_inset

given 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, leads to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

permanent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Response to an electric field addition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta e=-fd$
\end_inset

, is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $d-d_{0}=a^{-1}f$
\end_inset

 and lets us identify 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polarizability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple expression for the solvation energy of a rigid dipole 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d]=-b(d-d_{\ast})^{2}/2
\]

\end_inset

is sufficiently flexible to parametrize the electric cavity reaction field
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\ast}[d]=-\partial\mu/\partial d$
\end_inset

 to have the linear form with some, in general, non-zero intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\ast}[0]=-bd_{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that embedding a frozen 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gas phase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 system 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 into a solvent would lead to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d_{0}]=-\frac{b}{2}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 solvation energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, by minimizing the sum
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d]=e[d]+\mu[d]
\]

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 we find a new minimum (given that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<b<a$
\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{1}=\frac{ad_{0}-bd_{\ast}}{a-b}.
\]

\end_inset

 The values of the energy expression and solvation energy are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e[d_{1}]=\frac{a}{2}\left[\frac{b}{a-b}\right]^{2}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d_{1}]=-\frac{b}{2}\left[\frac{a}{a-b}\right]^{2}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

 The total is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]=-\frac{ab}{2(a-b)}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

The ratio of the changes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mu[d_{1}]-\mu[d_{0}]}{e[d_{1}]-e[d_{0}]}=-\left[2-\frac{b}{a}\right]
\]

\end_inset

is a negative number between 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $0<b<a$
\end_inset

 and is independent of system parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
 Naturally only the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 defining the scale of two contributions matters for this result.
 The relaxation effect of the free energy is 
\begin_inset Formula $o(b^{2})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]-G[d_{0}]=-\frac{b^{2}}{2(a-b)}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

to be compared to the 
\begin_inset Formula $o(b)$
\end_inset

 scale of 
\begin_inset Formula $G[d_{0}]$
\end_inset

.
 The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\to0$
\end_inset

 should be performed carefully, for instance, by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\ast}=-f_{\ast}/\epsilon$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $bd_{\ast}=-f_{\ast}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

 and discarding the divergent but 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-independent term off 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[d]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G[d]$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]-G[d_{0}]\to\frac{f_{\ast}^{2}}{2a}
\]

\end_inset

 and the ratio of the two contributions to this relaxation energy is exactly
 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
